    content: `<p>Chrome T-Rex Dinosaur Game 3D takes the beloved offline runner from Google Chrome and transforms it into an immersive behind-the-back experience. Instead of watching a pixelated T-Rex from the side, you&#8217;re placed directly behind the dinosaur as it sprints through a vibrant 3D desert landscape. The simple controls stay the same, but the added depth makes dodging cacti and pterodactyls feel completely fresh.</p>

<p>The original Chrome Dinosaur Game — also known as T-Rex Runner or Chrome Dino — is a built-in Easter egg that appears when you lose your internet connection. It was created by Google designers Sebastien Gabriel, Alan Bettes, and Edward Jung in 2014. The concept was a playful joke: no internet connection means you&#8217;re living in the &#8220;prehistoric ages.&#8221; What started as a clever offline distraction became internet culture, with approximately 270 million games played monthly.</p>

<p>The 3D version is a fan-made adaptation that reimagines the classic using WebGL and ThreeJS. The graphics were hand-crafted using MagicaVoxel software to maintain the same blocky, minimalist feel as the original while adding genuine depth. You&#8217;re no longer a spectator watching from the sidelines — you&#8217;re running directly behind the T-Rex, watching obstacles approach head-on. It changes the entire feel of the game while keeping the core mechanics intact.</p>

<p>What makes the 3D version challenging is the shift in perspective. In the original side-scrolling view, you can easily judge distances and timing. The behind-the-back camera makes depth perception trickier. Cacti that seemed easy to avoid now require more precise timing. The speed ramp-up feels more intense when obstacles are rushing toward you rather than scrolling past. It&#8217;s the same simple gameplay you know, but the new viewpoint creates a genuinely different experience.</p>

<p>The 3D adaptation showcases what the open-source community can do with a beloved classic. It keeps the pick-up-and-play simplicity while proving that even the most minimalist games can evolve without losing their charm.</p>

<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>How To Play Chrome T-Rex Dinosaur Game 3D</strong></h2>

<p>Press the spacebar or tap the screen to start the game. Your T-Rex begins running automatically through a 3D desert landscape.</p>

<p>Press spacebar or the up arrow key to jump over obstacles. On mobile devices, tap the screen to leap. Timing is everything — jump too early or too late and you&#8217;ll collide with cacti.</p>

<p>Press the down arrow key to duck under flying pterodactyls. These appear as you progress and add another layer of challenge to the endless run.</p>

<p>The game speeds up the longer you survive. What starts manageable becomes increasingly frantic as obstacles come faster and closer together. Stay focused and watch the horizon for incoming hazards.</p>

<p>Your score climbs continuously as you run. The goal is simple: survive as long as possible and beat your high score. One collision ends the game, but you can restart instantly and try again.</p>

<p>The 3D perspective makes judging distance trickier than the original side-view. Give yourself slightly more time to react than you would in the classic version. Watch for shadows on the ground to help gauge when obstacles are close.</p>

<p>The game runs directly in your browser with no downloads required. It works on both desktop and mobile devices.</p>
<div class='code-block code-block-1' style='margin: 8px auto; text-align: center; display: block; clear: both;'>

</div>
<!-- CONTENT END 1 -->`,
